GF vs Github.Copilot.Student:
---------------------------------------------
Create an python app with a modern GUI that satisfies the following requirements:

- the basic workflow is: the app lets the user pick some QASM3 file (from default dir: ./qasm/ ; default file at start-up: bell_state.qasm ) and have it loaded (read-only), live-edited (not saving the live changes), analysed (AST parse tree), transpiled (=prepared for the runtime by rewriting all (qiskit-qasm3-import)-unsupported expressions), represented as a quantum circuit graph, and finally automatically executed in 1 local qiskit runtime (initially we'll use qiskit_aer for local simulation, but later on we could switch to qiskit_ibm_runtime for remote execution on real quantum hw); the list of qiskit-supported features is found at: https://quantum.cloud.ibm.com/docs/en/guides/qasm-feature-table and https://quantum.cloud.ibm.com/docs/en/api/qiskit/circuit_library ;

- on top of this basic/monolithic execution of the QASM3 code, we also want the app to support a pseudo-distributed execution of the (transpiled) QASM3 code over N QPUs: unfortunately qiskit AER does not support inter-runtime quantum-communication (for qubit-sharing via entangled EPR-pairs, aka ebits), so the app cannot use multiple AER runtimes to simulate those N QPUs; instead it should use 1 single AER runtime and then visually represent the QPUs as sub-scopes, sharing qubits via teleportations (injected at chunk borders). The distributed workflow is: by right-clicking on some lines the user will pick some split-points in the original code (the app should suggest/highlight optimal split-points by KaHyPar hypergraph partitioning: https://github.com/kahypar ); each split-point will inject a custom pragma directive into previous line, the pragma being described in a custom grammar called DQC (which extends the official OpenQASM 3.1 grammar: https://github.com/openqasm/openqasm/tree/main/source/grammar ; both grammars are provided in the ./grammar/ dir), then the app will save this enriched code as a *.dqc file (under ./qasm.split/<original qasm filename>/ dir), and there it will also generate a new *.dqc.qasm file which is substituting each split pragma with a concatenation of as many quantum teleportations as needed for the qubits to be shared/exported to next chunk: notice that not all the qubits imported into next chunk/scope/QPU come from the previous chunk/scope/QPU (shared qubits may come from any chunks); when injecting the teleportations, we should assume that each scope/QPUs is connected to all the others in a mesh network allowing unrestricted exchange of qubits via teleportations (we also assume all scopes/QPUs have free/unlimited access to entangled EPR-pairs, consumed for teleportations across scopes/QPUS). The 2 classical bits of each teleportations are exchanged with classical methods (we assume all scopes have unrestricted access to those bits as well). If you need an example of QASM code for teleportation, you have one in teleport+.qasm ;

- GUI menus are:
    - File, View, Runtime, Help.
- File menuitems: "Load file ..." (for opening any file from disk), "Examples" (a quick shortcut to all files & subdirs under ./qasm/ dir, directly showed as dynamic menuitems); 
- View menuitems: Zoom in, Zoom out, Zoom reset, "Find ..." (for searching text in any text areas); 
- Runtime menuitems: "Run manually" (for re-running current live code without re-loading from disk, also allowing the user to input parameters if needed, e.g. qiskit-example.qasm ), "Qiskit shots (<current value>)" (for setting the iterations), "Timeout (<current value>)" (for setting a runtime timeout against infinite loops), Diagnostics (to show all libs versions, checking online for their updates, and showing timing and results of a simple smoke test on Hadamard gate for reference);
- Help menuitems: "GPL3 Licence" (link to: https://www.gnu.org/licenses/gpl-3.0.en.html ), Bibliography (dynamically showing the contents of biblio.url file as sub-menuitems, to be links to their URLs);

- the GUI should start maximized (100% of avail screen) and be sub-divided in the following areas (to be internally tabbed, when needed): Code, Graphs, Runtime; all areas should all be resizable (by dragging the dividers), zoomable (Ctrl +/-), scrollable, provided with a title-bar, and supporting right-click contextual menu with sensible options (except for the original code area, which uses right-click to mark split-points);
    - the Code area is placed top-left: it has 3 tabs (Original, Rewritten, Compatibility Rules);
        - the original qasm code should be editable (for live changes), showing line numbers (no word-wrapping), and should color runtime-unsupported expressions in red;
        - the rewritten code is transpiling on-the-fly the live original code so that it's prepared for running in qiskit runtime (by applying the rewriting rules), and each rewritten expression is highlighted in green and has a mouse-over 50%-transparent tooltip explaining shortly the change rationale (rule-ID, line# in original code, original expression); any runtime-unsupported expression missing a rewriting rule should be colored in red in this tab, and its mouse-over tooltip should show the error message;
        - "Compatibility Rules": for individually toggling the transpiling/rewriting rules (all active by default); initially these are the rewriting rules (all identified by an incremental rule-ID#): temporarily disable (and gray out) all the other rules without losing their toggles (this is handy to avoid losing custom preferences when debugging rule effects); drop all comments; drop all blank lines; injects "OPENQASM 3.1;" as first line, if the original code is missing an OPENQASM header; inject 'include "stdgates.inc";' as second line, if missing; rename (=add "my_" prefix to) custom gate names, if colliding with any gate defined in stdgates.inc;
    - the Graphs area is placed at the bottom (100% width): it has 4 tabs (based on the rewritten code by default, but the title bar should show a toggle to switch to the original code): AST parse-tree (by openqasm3 and/or antlr4-python3-runtime), Overall DAG, Qubit Interaction, Chunk Dependencies (with directed edges labeled with the vars, qubits and classical bits, that need to be exported/imported by each chunk); all graphs are zoomable (max zoom-out stops when fully visible), autofitting at load-time;
    - the Runtime area is placed top-right: it's not tabbed but split in 2 parts (resizable): the top part/area is taking 80% of height and it shows the overall circuit drawing (zoomable, scrollable, autofitting, max zoom-out at fully-visible image, draggable when not-fully-visible), while the bottom part/area (taking the remainder 20%) is showing the textual output of the execution, something like this:

Circuit summary: width=2 qubits, depth=3 parallel steps, size=3 gates, volume=...;
Rutime started at 2026-06-04 09:40:27.233 UTC, duration 00:00:01.551, shots 1024;
Measurement outcomes:
  readings -> occurrences (share of shots)
  11       -> 531 (51.86%)
  00       -> 493 (48.14%)
...
