Let's do an overall review of the dqc app (not the qasm3-to-qiskit, which is a read-only example dir). Let's give you some context: split pragmas are an extension described in my novel dqc*.g4 grammar, not part of the standard qasm3*.g4 grammar; for this reason, these pragmas should never be found in a *.qasm file, but only in *.dqc files; also: Compatibility rules control the Rewritten code live-view (and the live-graphs, like qiskit circuit, DAG, etc. depending on the Rewritten code), not the contents of the files on disk, nor the Original code live-view.
There are 2 typical workflows/espected behaviors:
(A) - the user opens a *.qasm file --> the user right-clicks to toggle/mark some split points --> the split pragmas are injected into the original code area (not the files): the Original code view becomes so live-modified (in RAM memory, not saved to disk yet), and all split lines are highlighted in yellow bg in the Original code view --> the user saves the live-modified code to a *.dqc file having the split pragmas on disk --> this save-action also generates (as a byproduct) a *.dqc.qasm file transforming each split pragma into a teleportation comment. This whole case (A) works regardless of rule #6 (split pragma to teleport comments) activation state, because (A) handles about file contents and Original code view (which is not under the control of compatibility rules).
(B) - the user opens a *.dqc file, which may already contain some split pragmas (from disk), and it may also get some extra split points added manually/live by the user (by right-clicking toggles, like in case A): all these split points should be highlighted in yellow bg in the Original code view (as usual), regardless of rule #6 activation state.

Finally: when rule #6 is active, the Rewritten code should transform each split pragma (regardless of it coming from disk or from user r-clicks) into a teleportation comment (colored in yellow, not green, for coherence with the pragma color).

Make sure the dqc app complies with the above workflows.
