this task is going to be hard: I need a rewriting rule to handle/workaround the uint type, which is unsupported by qiskit-qasm3-import frontend but is supported by the AER backend (according to https://quantum.cloud.ibm.com/docs/en/guides/qasm-feature-table#4 ). You may use any strategy you want to solve this problem, but maybe you could consider these hints (coming from another AI chatbot) first:
- you may use the supported bit[n] as a substitute for the unsupported uint[n], but only if that uint var is used for flow-control conditionals or counters, not for general uint math; this solution may also simplify the code by making uint-to-bool casting unneeded;
- you may transpile the uint into some longer code (like unfolding loops), but this is more complicated, prone to errors and can interfere badly with other rewriting rules; this is the solution used by run.py, but it's sub-optimal/lame;
- theoretically qiskit.circuit.classical can internally represent uint vars (via expr.Var), but only if they are built via python API, not via QASM parsing; e.g.: the following code is executable in AER (with DynamicCircuits support) and exportable into QASM3 with qiskit.qasm3.dumps(), which will correctly produce an "uint[8] counter" (unfortunately the other way around is not supported at the moment):

from qiskit import QuantumCircuit
from qiskit.circuit.classical import expr, types
qc = QuantumCircuit(3, 3)
counter = qc.add_var("counter", expr.lift(0, types.Uint(8)))
qc.measure(0, 0)
with qc.if_test(expr.equal(qc.clbits[0], expr.lift(1, types.Uint(1)))):
    qc.store(counter, expr.add(counter, expr.lift(1, types.Uint(8))))

Finally: test your solution against adder.qasm (which is using uint vars: a_in, b_in), and see if you can actually run+draw it.
